      <abstract>
        <p>Margie Engle has two fault-free rounds in quest to ride for United States equestrian team in Olympics (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Margie Engle of Wellington, Fla., moved two steps closer yesterday to ending her 20-year quest to ride for the United States equestrian team in the Olympics.</p>
        <p>Engle, a 41-year-old, six-time American Grand Prix Association rider of the year, guided Hidden Creek's Perin to two fault-free rounds in the second and third trials at Gladstone, N.J., to select a team of four horses and riders for the Sydney Games in September.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Margie Engle of Wellington, Fla., moved two steps closer yesterday to ending her 20-year quest to ride for the United States equestrian team in the Olympics.</p>
        <p>Engle, a 41-year-old, six-time American Grand Prix Association rider of the year, guided Hidden Creek's Perin to two fault-free rounds in the second and third trials at Gladstone, N.J., to select a team of four horses and riders for the Sydney Games in September.</p>
        <p>The 11-year-old German-bred gelding was error-free over 13 numbered obstacles requiring 16 jumping efforts within the 80-second time allowed in the morning round. Horse and rider duplicated that effort in the afternoon. Those two zeros, coupled with a zero fault score in Wednesday's first test, send them into tomorrow's final two rounds with a perfect score.</p>
        <p>After tomorrow, the top 12 horse-and-rider combinations will advance to a second and final set of five trials in California next month to determine the Olympic squad.</p>
        <p>Alison Firestone of Upperville, Va., piloted Jox to a clear round in the morning and four faults in the afternoon to sit in second place with 4.25 penalties. Raymond Texel of Beverly Hills, Calif., and his German-bred mare, Pershing, stood with 4.50 penalties.</p>
        <p>ALEX ORR Jr.</p>
